          "body": "Verse 3 is the psalm's only sustained description of threat, and it is deliberately overwhelming — three repetitions of *nahar* (floods/rivers), three repetitions of *nasa* (lifted up/raised), the pounding waves (*dokhi*, a rare and evocative term for the crashing, hammering surf). The anaphora is not decorative; it makes the reader feel the rising of the waters before the psalm silences them. Ancient Near Eastern religions — the Ugaritic Baal cycle especially — personified these waters as divine adversaries: Yam (Sea) and Nahar (River) were actual gods who challenged Baal's kingship. Israel's psalmist demythologizes them without diminishing them: the floods are real, their voice is loud, their pounding waves are mighty. Psalm 93 does not pretend the chaos is small. It acknowledges the full force of the opposition before making its claim. This is pastorally significant: the psalm is not written for people who feel no threat. It is written for people who feel the water rising, and it insists that the God who reigns is not surprised by the flood."
