          "body": "The psalm's final verse is its most unexpected and theologically dense. Having established YHWH's cosmic reign and His superiority over chaos, the psalmist pivots to two covenant realities: His testimonies (*edah*, revealed commands) are fully confirmed (*aman meod*, exceedingly trustworthy), and holiness (*qodesh*) befits His house forevermore. The logic is not incidental — it is the psalm's argument. A God who reigns over the cosmos, whose throne is from everlasting, and who is mightier than every chaotic force, is also a God whose word can be trusted absolutely. Cosmic sovereignty and revealed authority stand or fall together. If His throne is unshakeable, His testimony is unshakeable. And the appropriate response of those who dwell in His house — Israel, the temple community, the worshiping assembly — is holiness that mirrors His character. The psalm that began with the roar of floods ends in the silence of a holy house. Tim Keller's observation that biblical worship always moves from God's character to the worshiper's response applies precisely here: the psalmist has stared at the cosmic king for four verses and the only fitting conclusion is holiness in His presence, 'forevermore' (*le'orekh yamim*)."
